<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911113-0119</DOCNO><DOCID>911113-0119.</DOCID><HL>   TJX Plans Ventures   In Former Ames Sites;   Profit Declines 8.1%</HL><DATE>11/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ADD TJX</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)EARNINGS (ERN)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)EARNINGS (ERN)JOINT VENTURES (JVN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)FLORIDA (FL)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- TJX Cos. said it plans two newventures in as many as 15 former sites of Ames DepartmentStores for which TJX has lease liabilities.   Separately, TJX reported an 8.1% drop in third-quarter netincome to $27.4 million, or 39 cents a share, from $29.8million, or 42 cents a share, a year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   After the announcements yesterday, TJX shares plunged$1.25 to $14.625 in late New York Stock Exchange trading.   TJX said one of the new ventures will sell home fashionsin three sites &quot;in a nofrills, warehouse-like environment&quot;averaging about 50,000 square feet. The sites are scheduledto open in March 1992. The second business will be &quot;anindoor, value-oriented marketplace&quot; of booths occupied byindependent retailers, TJX said. Four of these stores willopen in Florida at the beginning of 1992, with eight futuresites considered for later in the year.   Although the businesses will be run as profit centers, TJXsaid they were conceived to help defray the costs of theformer leases and will be an opportunity to test newconcepts.   In the past two years, TJX has been forced to assumerental-payment obligations for 120 former Zayre departmentstore properties after Ames filed for bankruptcy-courtprotection. A predecessor company of TJX had sold the Zayreunits to Ames.   In the latest quarter, TJX's sales rose 9.2% to $705.3million from $646 million. In the nine months, profit fell4.7% to $56.1 million, or 80 cents a share, from $58.8million, or 84 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 13%to $1.96 billion from $1.73 billion.</TEXT></DOC>